
[1]oppress

   OPPRESS', v.t. [L. appressus, from opprimo; ob and premo, to press.]

   1. To load or burden with unreasonable impositions; to treat with
   unjust severity, rigor or hardship; as, to oppress a nation with taxes
   or contributions; to oppress one by compelling him to perform
   unreasonable service.

   2. To overpower; to overburden; as, to be oppressed with grief.

   3. to sit or lie heavy on; as, excess of good oppresses the stomach.
